SIMPLE: turning
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Turning
<hw>Turn"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act
of one who, or that which, turns; also, a winding; a bending course; a
flexure; a meander.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through paths and <qex>turnings</qex> often trod by day.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The place of a turn; an angle or corner, as of a
road.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is preached at every <qex>turning</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Deviation from the way or proper course.</def>
<rj><au>Harmar.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Turnery, or the shaping of solid substances into
various forms by means of a lathe and cutting tools.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The pieces, or chips, detached in
the process of turning from the material turned; -- usually used in the
plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A maneuver by which an enemy or a
position is turned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Turning and boring mill</b></col>, <cd>a kind of lathe
having a vertical spindle and horizontal face plate, for turning and
boring large work.</cd> -- <col><b>Turning bridge</b></col>. <cd>See the
Note under <er>Drawbridge</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Turning
engine</b></col>, <cd>an engine lathe.</cd> -- <col><b>Turning
lathe</b></col>, <cd>a lathe used by turners to shape their work.</cd>
-- <col><b>Turning pair</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under <er>Pair</er>,
<pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>Turning point</b></col>, <cd>the point
upon which a question turns, and which decides a case.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turningness</ent>⟦br⟧
